fields.description:
It would be beneficial to have a contextual menu to apply a file from a stash to the working copy:
{noformat}
git checkout stash@{<X>} -- <filename>
{noformat}
Could possibly implement this with a custom action, but there is no parameter to be able to access a specific stash (or a file in a given stash).

Git flow doesn't work. When I start a new feature:

{noformat}
sh.exe C:\Users\Martijn\AppData\Local\Atlassian\SourceTree\gitflow_local\gitflow\git-flow feature start release-16
C:\Users\Martijn\AppData\Local\Atlassian\SourceTree\gitflow_local\gitflow\git-flow: line 39: $'\r': command not found

C:\Users\Martijn\AppData\Local\Atlassian\SourceTree\gitflow_local\gitflow\git-flow: line 52: syntax error near unexpected token `$'{\r''
C:\Users\Martijn\AppData\Local\Atlassian\SourceTree\gitflow_local\gitflow\git-flow: line 52: `usage() {
'



Completed with errors, see above.
{noformat}

I can perfectly well create a stash, but I cannot apply nor delete it. When I delete it, well, see screenshot.

When I apply it:
{noformat}
git -c diff.mnemonicprefix=false -c core.quotepath=false stash apply stash@{0}
fatal: ambiguous argument 'stash@0': unknown revision or path not in the working tree.

Use '--' to separate paths from revisions, like this:
'git <command> [<revision>...] -- [<file>...]'
{noformat}

The only way I can get a stash to apply itself is by switching to a command prompt and doing:
{noformat}
git stash apply 'stash@{0}'
{noformat}

When I leave the quotes out, I get the exact same error as I get in sourcetree, so I suggest sourcetree must also use quotes. Apparently.
